  "prompt": "Why do secants have a vertical asymptote?",
  "response": "Secant functions, denoted by \\( \\sec(x) \\), are defined as the reciprocal of cosine functions: \n\n\\[ \\sec(x) = \\frac{1}{\\cos(x)} \\]\n\nVertical asymptotes occur when the function approaches infinity or negative infinity. For secant functions, vertical asymptotes happen at the values of \\( x \\) where \\( \\cos(x) = 0 \\). This is because division by zero is undefined in mathematics, and \\( \\sec(x) \\) becomes unbounded (approaches infinity or negative infinity) in these cases.\n\nThe cosine function \\( \\cos(x) \\) is zero at odd multiples of \\( \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\):\n\n\\[ x = (2k+1)\\frac{\\pi}{2} \\]\n\nwhere \\( k \\) is any integer. At these points, \\( \\sec(x) \\) is undefined and thus exhibits vertical asymptotes. Therefore, secant functions have vertical asymptotes at \\( x = (2k+1)\\frac{\\pi}{2} \\) for any integer \\( k \\).",
